<title><i>||hara</i> and <i>Tto</i></title>
<summary><i>The Bushmen anoint their heads with //hára (which is black and sparkling), mixed with fat, and rub their bodies with ttò. (L VIII.-14. 7272 rev.,-7276 rev., note). Ttò or &apos;Roode Klip&apos; is dug out from the mountain side. Precautions to be taken against sorcerers upon these occasions. (L VIII.-14. 7275 and 7276, 7279 and 7380). </i>A description of stones called ||<i>hara</i> and <i>tto. ||hara</i> is black and the people pound it together with fat and anoint their heads with it. <i>Tto</i> is red and is pounded and rubbed onto their flesh.</summary><comments>1) This story is found in Book VIII-14</comments><date>August 1878</date><storypages>7272v-7276v</storypages><category>Custom and daily life</category><author>|han≠kass'o (Klein Jantje) (VIII)</author><keyword><kw>stone</kw><subkw>called tto, or rooi klip</subkw></keyword>
